han affluent women. Education systems, tax codes, labor laws, public polices, and cultural beliefs about motherhood and marriage all make a difference. Any accounting of "who does what" needs to consider the complicity of trade unions, state arrangements for children's schooling, and new cultural prescriptions for a happy marriage. With its cross-national perspective, this pioneering volume speaks not only to sociologists concerned with gender and family, but also to those interested in scholarship on states, public policy, culture, and social inequality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aHousekeepingxSocial aspectsvCross-cultural studies. 0aSex rolevCross-cultural studies. 0aSexual division of laborvCross-cultural studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marriage & Family.2bisacsh1 aDrobnič, Sonja, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTreas, Judith, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804773744zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804773744423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804773744.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles